# many Fuzion types are orderable, so we can just sort them using
items.sort

# if, however, we have a comparator Function c that takes two arguments a and b
# and returns a bool that is true iff a <= b, we can define an orderable feature
# using `c` as follows
c_order(val) : property.orderable is
  cmp(b c_order.this) => c val b.val
  public redef type.lteq(a, b c_order.this) bool => a.cmp b

# and then sort using this order:
items.sort_by c_order
